b'' b'i wrote that i thought that peter meant, "no prophecy of' b'scripture (or, as one reader suggests, no written prophecy) is' b'merely the private opinion of the writer."' b'' b'tony zamora replies (sat may that this in turn implies that' b'it is not subject to the private interpretation of the reader' b'either. i am not sure that i understand this.' b'in one sense, no statement by another is subject to my private' b'interpretation. if reliable historians tell me that the athenians' b'lost the pelopennesian war, i cannot simply interpret this away' b'because i wanted the athenians to win. facts are facts and do not go' b'away because i want them to be otherwise.' b'in another sense, every statement is subject to private' b'interpretation, in that i have to depend on my brains and' b'expereience to decide what it means, and whether it is sufficiently' b'well attested to merit my assent. even if the statement occurs in an' b'inspired writing, i still have to decide, using my own best' b'judgement, whether it is in fact inspired. this is not arrogance b'it is just an inescapable fact.' b'' b'yours,' b'james kiefer' 